##Quarantine in Iran | noon

Micro Signal noon-story

Feature description, staring back at the Times with stories

The days of isolation in Iran

Dictation | Sun Jianlong
Interview, by Yang Xi

1

At 10:30 a.m. local time on March 5, an Iranian friend of mine was waiting for a bus at the bus station south of Tehran, ready to leave for another city, Isfahan.

There are fewer people than ever before. He saw a convoy of vehicles arrive at the bus station, their pick-up trucks loaded with disinfectant. When the convoy stopped, disinfectant workers in protective clothing, carrying disinfectant solution on their backs, gathered to take photos, accompanied by local media. He was very friendly, and when he saw my friend, he gave him a pair of protective gloves and told him to stay away from the line.

In the past week or so, Iran has begun the initial large-scale disinfection of subway and bus stations based on the available epidemic prevention materials. At the entrance of the bus station hall, there are also staff members with warm guns to check the body temperature of the passengers. But there are still not many people wearing masks inside and outside the station.

I live in northern Tehran and am a resident employee of a trading company in Zhejiang Province. I have not been outside since the Iranian Ministry of Health announced a new case of coronavirus pneumonia in Iran on 19 February. In addition to me, the company employs several Iranian staff locally, and we have been working from home recently.

Although the local government has some cover-up of the outbreak, everything is fine on my end at the moment. Because I had heard some gossip before, so I made some preparations ahead of time, bought a lot of vegetables and meat stored in the refrigerator, there are chicken wings, beef, pork, cabbage, potatoes, peppers... are durable, at least enough to eat more than a month.

There are several large supermarkets in Tehran with a good selection of goods. Recently, due to the epidemic, the supermarkets are almost completely sold out at night. Everyone's shopping carts are piled high. In addition, there are many small shops on the street, a street may open dozens of. In general, Iran is well supplied, but prices have risen recently, especially for ginger and garlic -- as if it were precautionary -- as if Foshan were more than twice as much as 60 yuan a kilogram.

Face masks have gone up in price and are no longer available. On February 19, the pharmacy suddenly began to line up and the stock was sold out. In the past, the average medical mask cost about RMB 2030 yuan per face mask. Later, it rose to RMB 34, and the N95 mask rose from RMB 5 to RMB thirty.

At first, there were very few people on the street wearing masks, and they thought it was rude to talk to people in masks -- as if only patients wore masks. And the Iranian people feel that this virus and ordinary flu is no different, sick are the elderly, if really sick to go to the mosque worship. These days, many Iranians still attend Friday prayers at the mosque. It was not until March 6 that the Iranian Ministry of Health announced the cancellation of a week of nationwide worship and the closure of nearly 60,000 mosques. For the first time in the 41 year history of the Islamic republic, religious activity has been halted because of the outbreak.

There is also a reason, Iran's domestic gap between the rich and the poor is particularly large. Tehran is built on a mountain. According to the locals, I live in the fabled area of the rich in the north and the relatively poor in the south. The poor don't even have enough to eat. They eat naan and drink tea at most every day. They can't afford to buy masks, and I don't have it.

Early last month, I was flying back to Tehran from Bandar Abbas, a coastal city in southern Iran, when I saw some Iranians wearing masks at the airport. They see a Chinese or Asian face -- in Iran almost all Chinese -- as if to duck, or to say, impatiently, "Corona" . When I boarded the plane, I walked inside to find a seat, and people without masks covered their mouths when they saw me pass.

Then one night, I went to a famous restaurant in Tehran with my local Chinese friends. In a taxi, the driver would joke, do you have this virus? We laughed and explained that we didn't. At the restaurant door, the waiter asked, are you Chinese? We said yes, he said sorry, Chinese can not go in. I was embarrassed. The Iranians are actually quite friendly to the Chinese, but I wouldn't rule out the possibility that a few people might say, you're Chinese, you have a virus, you can't come in.

The streets of Tehran are crowded with shops

2

I graduated from a university in Shaoxing after 1995, majoring in finance. I spent some time in a securities company before joining the Foreign Trade Company. In 2018, I was posted to Tehran after just six months, when the company wanted to do business in Iran. Iran is a relatively safe and china-friendly country in the Middle East, so I'm not too worried.

After getting off the plane, I took a taxi from the airport to my residence. Both sides of the highway were desert. I felt as if I had come to the "great northwest" . In fact, Tehran is more modern, and before 1979 more Westernized. The city of more than 13 million people, the flow of people is also large, people take the subway, buses to work, the suburbs are also connected to the subway, subway is made in China.

I wasn't used to it when I first got here, but I got used to it. There are four or five Chinese restaurants in Tehran, and one of them, from the owner to the chef, is Chinese, and is very well known there, and I used to go there often. The restaurant has been closed since February 9th.

Other restaurants will take your temperature at the door and give you a mask and gloves. The same is true inside the mall, which is open even though there are fewer people than before. Including some Chinese who set up factories here, they want to shut down, but the customers say no, what if you shut me down? After all, the national situation is different, tell them to stop production, or Fengcun, Fengshe community, I think it is impossible. The first outbreak was in Qom, a holy city where Shia Muslims from all over the world make pilgrimages to Qom, making it difficult to close the city. And since Iran's economy is already weak, shutting it down would only add to its woes.

Iranians always feel that the Chinese eat not clean, they sometimes see CCTV-4, said the Chinese pick a thing in the field to eat, do not wash, very terrible. Some people also asked me if I ate cats, dogs, bats and so on, and I was very angry. They think the Chinese eat everything. At first I would explain that this is just a habit of a small number of Chinese people. And then I didn't bother to explain. The other day I got an Instagram post from an Iranian friend who joked about whether you were eating bats?

I am an extrovert and have made a lot of Iranian friends. Most of them were older than I was, forty or 12 years old, and they'd met through work, and then they'd become friends. These days, they still go out to work normally, the precautions are better, wear masks and gloves, do not go out to dinner at night, just stay at home.

When there was no outbreak, I was often invited to their home in the evenings. Iranian homes are very clean, very beautiful, every home carpet, a door to take off their shoes. Dinner wasn't till 90:00, and then we'd have tea and talk, and I'd be home by 12:00. Praise them from time to time for their good cooking and good looks.

Perhaps because Iran has always been under sanctions, people have gotten used to it and are more optimistic. If a minor illness, they do not go to the hospital, is often a worse situation before going to the hospital, so the death rate is particularly high. Others feel that it is God's will to make them sick and do not worry about it. Now Iran's Ministry of Health is also relatively strict, starting from March 2, sent 300,000 teams to check each family.

There are fewer people and fewer cars on Tehran's streets, about half as many as usual. A few days ago, an Iranian friend in bazaar, south of Tehran, sent me a couple of photos. It was 10 o'clock in the morning. It used to be full of people at this time. Now many shops are closed.

The Iranian government did not implement the mandatory quarantine measures because of the shortage of anti-epidemic materials. There are vendors on the subway carrying three non-product masks over their shoulders, as well as disposable masks. I have been self-isolation for 16 days, usually do not go out, occasionally go out to buy food, only to see on the road about a third of the people wearing masks, many people still run around, really worried about them.

3

From the end of last year to the beginning of this year, several things have happened in Iran, and the people are very angry with the government. First, the rise in oil prices triggered large-scale protests. At that time, the Internet communication was so bad that I couldn't answer every day. I could only contact the country by international phone or text message. It took me about ten days to get back to normal.

Then, senior Army of the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution General Sulejmani was killed in an air strike in Iraq. When news of the death reached Iran, people were shocked and a sense of cohesion was created. But five days later, there was another crash. At first the Iranian military denied it, but later it was announced that the plane had been shot down by its own government.

Then came the outbreak in China, and the focus shifted. The Iranians were laughing at us at first, but now they're laughing at themselves, and a lot of people are starting to question the government. Why didn't they say so earlier? There are two other big events in February: The 41st anniversary of the Islamic Revolution and Iran's 11th parliamentary elections. If the government had been open about the outbreak, no one would have wanted to go out on the streets to celebrate or vote. Now that the election is over, the government has been slow to release some figures. The numbers are likely to continue to creep up over the next week, with many previously undiagnosed cases.

In my conversations with my Iranian friends, I can sense that they are not happy with the government, but for now, a lot of people have to eat first. Iran has done a good job, the poor to buy Naan are subsidized by the government, the price is relatively low. Without sesame, a large piece of Naan might be worth as little as 1-1.5 yuan, enough for one person for a day. They usually go with fried eggs, vegetables, and cheese, or better yet, grilled chicken or lamb chops. But the rich don't just eat. Many of them emigrate to Canada, Los Angeles or Europe rather than stay in Iran. Here, all the wealth and power is concentrated in the few.

I've been in Tehran for almost three years, and I honestly don't think it's changed much. A few years ago, and a few years later. This place is so slow, it could take a decade to build a high-rise. Ask a worker to carry a load, the Chinese take a few hours, the Iranians take a few days, they carry on and run to drink tea and chat with others.

I often get asked by young Iranians if I can get him a job. Iran is not as prosperous as China's tertiary sector of the economy, with few jobs, an oversupply of workers and high unemployment. Young people, even if they go all the way to school, have a degree, and jobs are hard to find. They don't have a lot of choices. They may go to the government or the bank, or to the traffic police, or to the shops, or to hotels or restaurants. But if he spoke English or Chinese and worked as an interpreter for a Chinese company, he would earn a respectable $1,500 a month, according to media reports, and their minimum wage was $92 a month.

Many people in Iran can speak Chinese. Two days ago, an Iranian Internet celebrity, Meng Yaqi, posted a video in Chinese thanking China for medical aid. In fact, I know a lot of Iranians whose Chinese is better than hers. Learning Chinese is a fashionable thing in Iran. After Iran granted visa-free access to China in July last year, some Iranians began learning Chinese to prepare for the guided tour industry. The average salaryman earns only a thousand yuan a month, but as a tour guide he can get up to a hundred dollars a day and still be free.

I haven't been back home since 2018. Many of my Chinese friends returned to China around February 25, and I had planned to stay. It would be months before I could come back, and I was afraid I'd miss too much at work. Although I am also worried about the number of infected people in Iran, the situation is out of control, but at present I am more optimistic. Besides, if it gets better over time, I'll have a lot of opportunities, and I won't have a lot of competition.

But recently the company told me that they must send me back to China. In the early morning of March 8, I took my friend to the Imam International Airport in Tehran, where he was to catch a 4:30 flight back to Zhengzhou. Armed with protective gear, we didn't talk much in the car, but each wished the other well. In a couple of days, I will return to my country too, feeling a bit reluctant to part with it, hoping that the epidemic will soon be over and normal economy and life will resume.
